<div id="about_swingoutlondon">
	<h1 class="section_heading">About Swing Out London</h1>

    <p>This website is mainly for <%= link_to "Me", {:anchor => "about_me"}, {:rel =>"subsection"} %>. There - I've said it: it presents the information I want to see, the way I want to see it and it's my main way of personally deciding where I want to dance. If it's useful to other people as well, then I'm very glad.</p>

    <p>We are incredibly privileged in London to have such a great range of opportunities for dancing available to us. The problem is finding out about those opportunities.</p>

    <p>I was frustrated when starting out that I couldn't find any comprehensive Lindy Hop listings and although I later found out about existing services like <%= link_to "Swing Junction", "http://www.swingjunction.co.uk/modules/piCal/index.php?cid=1"%> , <%= link_to "Swing Dancers Of London", "http://www.swingdancersoflondon.org/"%> and Judy's List (an email list - ask an experienced dancer) they don't provide exactly what I want, so I decided to make my own site (as you do).</p>

    <p>In some respects London is quite a divided scene with a lot of dancers unaware of what's going on outside the bubble of the first swing school they came across.</p>
	
	<p>I think that independent community-founded organisations like <%= link_to "Swing Dancers Of London", "http://www.swingdancersoflondon.org/"%> and the <%= link_to "London Lindy Exchange", "http://londonlindyexchange.com/ "%> are really important and I want to follow in their footsteps by providing a great service independently of any of the swing schools. </p>
	
	<p>Swing Out London has been live since August 2010 and the listings were last updated at <%=@last_updated_time%> on  <%=@last_updated_date%>.</p>



    <h2 class="section_heading" id="show_love_header">Show some love</h2>

    <p>If you like Swing Out London and find it useful, please consider linking to it from your Blog, Facebook, <%= link_to "Twitter", "http://twitter.com/swingoutlondon", :title => "Swing Out London on Twitter"%> or personal website: this really helps Google to know that people are interested and will make it easier for others to find the site. </p>
    
    <p>It's always nice to get <%=mail_to CONTACT_EMAIL, "Email"%> as well.</p>

    



    <h2 id="listings_policy_header" class="section_heading">Listings Policy</h2>
    
    <ul id="listings_policy">  
        <li>
            <h3>20s-40's Dance styles </h3>
            <p>The focus is on <% link_to "Lindy Hop", "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lindy_Hop" %> (8-count, 6-count and 30's Charleston) but 
                <%= link_to "Blues", "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blues_dance#Blues_dancing_in_the_contemporary_swing_dance_community" %>
                <%= link_to "Balboa", "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balboa_(dance)"%>,
                <%= link_to "Shag", "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collegiate_shag"%>, 
                and 
                <%= link_to "1920's Charleston", "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charleston_(dance)"%> are also listed since many Lindyhoppers also dance these styles. 
            </p>
            <p><%= link_to "Jitterbug", "http://swungover.wordpress.com/2010/11/09/the-definition-of-jitterbug/" %> is included (on the borderline), but generally nights which are primarily 50's Jive or Rock and Roll are out, as are modern jive, west coast swing and anything of that sort.</p>
            <p> The world seems to Love <%= link_to "Electro Swing", "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electroswing" %> at the moment, but I don't, so it's out. If you're really interested, there's a regular night at <%= link_to "The Book Club", "http://www.wearetbc.com/" %> in Shoreditch.</p>
        </li>   
        <li>
            <h3>Only in London </h3>
            <p>Listings are only for events within the M25 and usually those which are on the London transport network (i.e. places you can get a night bus home from!).</p>
        </li>   
        <li>
            <h3>Regular classes...</h3>
            <p>I try and list all of the <em>regular</em> dance classes for the dance styles mentioned above - that means weekly drop-in classes and also courses which take place over a number of weeks but repeat regularly. </p>
        </li>   
        <li>
            <h3>...but not workshops</h3>
            <p>There are also many one-off workshops and classes going on in London, but keeping track of those is much more than I can handle: try the websites of the individual swing schools to find out about these.</p>
    
            <p>I will however tweet about anything particularly interested coming up (especially <%= link_to "aerials", "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aerial_(dance_move)"%> workshops) on the <%= link_to "Swing Out London twitter feed", "http://twitter.com/swingoutlondon", :title => "Swing Out London on Twitter"%>.</p>
        </li>   
        <li>
            <h3>All social dancing...</h3>
            <p>I try and list all of the opportunities for dancing Lindy Hop in London over the next 14 days and the main nights for related styles.</p> 
        </li>   
        <li>    
            <p>The exceptions are smaller venues like <%= link_to "The Swan at The Globe", "http://www.swanattheglobe.co.uk/#/newscontact/events/"%> and <%= link_to "The Quecumbar", "http://www.quecumbar.co.uk/"%>: while they put on great Swing bands, they can only accommodate a handful of Balboa dancers at best and aren't really suitable for <%= link_to "lindy-bombing", "http://wikibin.org/articles/lindy-bombing.html"%>.</p>
        </li>   
        <li>
            <h3>...including vintage clubs</h3>
            <p>I Love getting dressed up in vintage attire and going out to a club like <%= link_to "the Blitz party", "www.theblitzparty.com"%> or <%= link_to "Die Freche Muse", "http://www.diefrechemuse.co.uk/"%> where the music is swinging and everyone looks fabulous. These nights aren't aimed at dancers, but if you Bring Your Own there's often a great time to be had, as well as a crowd of admiring Civilians (non-dancers).</p>
        </li>   
        <li>
            <h3>...and swing gigs</h3>
            <p>London has a solid bunch of trad jazz and swing bands like <%= link_to "The Shirt Tail Stompers", "http://shirttailstompers.com/"%>, <%= link_to "Top Shelf Jazz", "http://www.topshelfjazz.co.uk/"%> and <%= link_to "The Sax Pastilles", "www.saxpastilles.co.uk/"%> playing great dancing music. You'll see them around town playing Lindy socials, but they also sometimes play straight gigs where there is room to dance. Again it's usually a case of <acronym title="Bring Your Own">BYO</acronym> dancers.</p>
        </li>
    </ul>

</div>



<div id="about_me">
	<h3 class="section_heading">About me</h3>
	<p>I live in South London, I've been dancing Lindy since late 2009, and I love it.</p>
	<p>I have a blog called "<%= link_to "Why I Dance...", "http://whyidance.tumblr.com/"%>" which does exactly what it says on the tin.</p>
	<p>Leads in London don't get to meet and talk to each other so much, so I organise <%= link_to "London Lindy Leads Dinners", "http://www.facebook.com/home.php?sk=group_147221981989905"%> to try and fix that.</p>
	<p>I dance all over town and I've tried to have lessons from each of the London swing schools. I mainly dance Lindy Hop (6 &amp; 8 count and Charleston), but also some Blues and I'm keen to learn more 1920's style Charleston.</p>
	<p>Please send any comments, corrections or listings to <%=mail_to CONTACT_EMAIL%></p>
</div>

